@NODE OtherPrograms
@{U}Other Programs@{UU}

This section describes interactions with other programs as I become aware
of them. If you see some interaction with CallerID and another program,
please @{" Contact Me " link Contact} as quickly as posible with any information you can provide.

SnoopDOS     Excesive activity is visable when using SnoopDOS while CallerID
             is running. This is because the environment processing routine
             that I currently use requires LOCKING of environment variables.
             Also there is some directory changing going on. This takes
             quite little processor time but can be anoying when you try to
             use SnoopDOS on other programs.

             The Fix: Either tell SnoopDOS to ignore CallerID completely, or
                      have SnoopDOS not watch the LOCK and CHANGE DIR status.

                      I may rewrite the routines to stop this in the future.
@ENDNODE


@NODE Introduction
@{U}Introduction@{UU}

GS CallerID was written for one simple reason... 
There wasn't anything that would do the job I wanted done.

I found and tried a few Caller ID programs. One had a lot of features, 
but didn't actually work with the modem in the unregistered version so 
I wasn't about to pay for it blindly. One worked, but didn't do 
anything other that what my little box on the wall can do. The others 
simply didn't work properly.

So I decided to write a program myself. 

This little program has a lot of nice features and will have more in 
the next version. I just wanted to get the program out to the people 
in this simple working form and add the rest later.

In short, GS CallerID makes use of a CallerID modem and monitors incoming 
calls. Each call is recorded to a history buffer and if a valid phone 
number comes in (not out of area or private or error) the number can be 
logged in to a @{" Black Book " link BlackBook} where you can keep track of friends and family 
and any one else you want. You can even use the @{" Black Book " link BlackBook} to configure 
special handling of incoming calls. For example, pickup and hang up on 
people who are really annoying, answer with a modem tone then hang up if 
they are really really annoying, or call external programs to answer 
(such as a FAX program).

For details on the current and future features, take a look at the @{" Operation " link Operation}
and @{" Expectation " link Expectation} sections of this manual.

If you like this program and want to unlock all of the power it has, 
simply fill in the @{" Registration " link Registration} form and send it to me 
with the proper fee.

Enjoy this software and happy computing!
@ENDNODE

@NODE Installation
@{U}Installation@{UU}

Installing GS CallerID is quite simple.

Place the Icon in the drawer where you want it and double click!

I would recommend the WBStartup drawer so the program is launched each 
time you reboot your computer. This will ensure you get full use of this 
program and catch as many calls as possible.

You can simply start the installer script included with this archive
to get the program installed and create the basic configuration file
for your system.


I run a BBS so my computer is running 24 hours a day. 

I keep an extra modem on the voice line just for use with this program 
and my FAX program so it works out well for me.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Configuration
@{U}Configuration@{UU}

Configuring GS CallerID requires a text editor at this point. 

A GUI editor will be added at a later time.



Sorry, but that is just the way I like to do things. Makes it much easier 
to have all the configuration files in one location.

The name of the configuration file is CallerID.cfg (SUPRIZE!) 
and is created the first time you run the CallerID program.

Here is a list of the options you can set and descriptions of what each 
one does and proper values....

   @{" DEVICE         " link DEVICE}   @{" UNIT           " link UNIT}   @{" BAUD           " link BAUD}
   @{" SHARED         " link SHARED}   @{" RESET          " link RESET}   @{" CID            " link CID}
   @{" CIDDATE        " link CIDDATE}   @{" CIDTIME        " link CIDTIME}   @{" CIDNMBR        " link CIDNMBR}
   @{" CIDNAME        " link CIDNAME}   @{" CIDMODE        " link CIDMODE}   @{" OFFHOOK        " link OFFHOOK}
   @{" ONHOOK         " link ONHOOK}   @{" TONEANSWER     " link TONEANSWER}   @{" SLOWMODEM      " link SLOWMODEM}
   @{" ACTION         " link ACTION}   @{" PATH           " link PATH}   @{" DEBUG          " link DEBUG}
   @{" X              " link X}   @{" Y              " link Y}   @{" SMALLX         " link SMALLX}
   @{" SMALLY         " link SMALLY}   @{" BBX            " link BBX}   @{" BBY            " link BBY}
   @{" BACKGROUND     " link BACKGROUND}   @{" BBBACKGROUND   " link BBBACKGROUND}   @{" WARNBACKGROUND " link WARNBACKGROUND}
   @{" TEXTCOLOR      " link TEXTCOLOR}   @{" SHADOWCOLOR    " link SHADOWCOLOR}   @{" SECONDS        " link SECONDS}
   @{" HISTORY        " link HISTORY}   @{" BBMAX          " link BBMAX}   @{" SHOWTIME       " link SHOWTIME}
   @{" SHOWDATE       " link SHOWDATE}   @{" BACKUP         " link BACKUP}   @{" FIXCLOCK       " link FixClock}
   @{" FIRSTRING      " link Rings}   @{" MORERINGS      " link Rings}   @{" BBONLY         " link BBONLY}
   @{" FAX            " link FAX}   @{" FAXCMD         " link FAXCMD}   @{" CONNECT        " link CONNECT}
   @{" CONNECTCMD     " link CONNECTCMD}

NOTICE: If you are an unregistered user, all of this information is
        of no value. Although you can edit and save your settings, the 
        GS CallerID program won't read them off of the disk. This is the 
        only way I could think of to make the program functional enough 
        for everyone while encouraging software @{" registration " link Registration}. Sorry, but 
        I have gotten stiffed on too many programs in the past.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Operation
@{U}Operation@{UU}

The operation of the GS CallerID program is rather "hands off" for the 
most part. You simply let the program run and it will monitor the modem 
for incoming calls and pop open a window then one comes in. Now that 
seems rather easy. Launch it and forget it.

But, this program is able to offer so much more!


There are @{" 3 buttons " link 3Buttons} on the history window and several
@{" menu options " link Menu} for both the history window and the @{" Black Book " link BlackBook}
allong with several @{" key controls " link KeyControls} that help you work with
the information stored by this program.



With the history review buffer you can look back and see who has called. 
Every call is logged to the history review buffer file (up to the maximum 
number specified in the config file). If the same person calls three 
times, each of the calls will show up in the review list. This offers you 
the chance to see the calls in the order they came in. Not just when one 
person last called like most of the normal caller ID boxes you can buy.

To access the review buffer, you simply click on the CallerID window 
(or title bar if in stand by mode) and the window will become activated. 
you use the arrow keys (up/down & left/right) to move through the list. 
The number in the title bar within parentheses will indicate how far 
back in history you are looking. Entry (1) is the most recent call. 
Pressing the UP arrow will move up the list (increasing the entry number) 
and move you further back in history. If you reach the end of the list 
you wrap around to the beginning of the list. And pressing the DOWN 
arrow will do just the reverse. The left and right keys are simply added 
ways of doing the same thing. Left is back in history and Right is closer 
to the present. There is a special entry (0) which is simply the title 
of the program. This is so you won't forget me.

You can @{" take a look " link History.iff/main} at the History window before
we get started if you want. It will show you all the features of the window
including the @{" three buttons " link 3Buttons}.

As call come in, one of three things will happen.

	1) This will be a new call with no phone number attaches. 
	   Such as an "Out Of Area" call or "Private Number" call 
	   where the CallerID information from the phone company 
	   doesn't provice a phone number. These calls are displayed 
	   as best as the computer can Simply posting the information 
	   provided and going on it's way.

	2) This will be a new call with a phone number attached. 
	   This is the normal result of an incoming call from a 
	   CallerID supported area. Since this is a new number to the 
	   program, the name of the caller (if available) along with 
	   the time, date, and phone number will be added to the 
	   @{" Black Book " link BlackBook} file (if there is room as specified in the config 
	   file).

Steps 1 and 2 are much like what a standard CallerID unit would provide 
with the exception for the @{" Black Book " link BlackBook} and the tracking of ALL calls. The 
exciting part comes in step 3....

	3) This will be a repeat call. A number that is known to the 
	   system calls again. The program will take a quick look into 
	   the @{" Black Book " link BlackBook} file and grab out some valuable information. 
	   Such as a replacement name! The caller's address, the action
	   to be performed for this caller, and possibly some other 
	   notes you have added to the file. 
		
	   All of this information (accept for the action) will be 
	   displayed in the incoming call window. This will give you a 
	   great deal of information about the caller that you can't get 
	   in any other CallerID device that I have seen. Heck, you can 
	   even mark some numbers as CLICK action where once the phone 
	   rings (usually twice) it is answered and then hung up. This 
	   is rather rude so reserve it for people you really don't want 
	   to talk to!



Now that I have given you a quick run down of the incoming call window 
with it's history, lets take a closer look at that wonderful @{" Black Book " link BlackBook}.
and the @{" three buttons " link 3Buttons} on the history window.
@ENDNODE


@NODE Menu
@{U}Menu Items@{UU}

	@{fg shine}History@{fg text}			@{fg shine}Black Book@{fg text}
	@{" Load Config " link LoadConfig}		@{" Add Entry   " link AddBB}
	@{" Save Config " link SaveConfig}		@{" Kill Entry  " link KillBB}
	@{" Configure   " link Config}		@{" Sort        " link SortBB}
	@{" Black Book  " link BlackBook}		@{" Quit        " link QuitBB}
	@{" Trim        " link TrimHist}
	@{" Quit        " link QuitHist}
@ENDNODE


@NODE LoadConfig
@{U}Load Config@{UU}

	This menu item will read the S:CallerID.cfg file. This is
	automaticaly done at start up. But you may want to edit
	the config file and would then need to reload this file.
	
	You can edit the @{" config " link Configuration} file with any text editor. And
	the text editor of your choice can be started with the
	@{" Configure " link Config} menu item.


	@{fg shine}@{U}ARexx Command@{UU}@{fg text}
	LOADCFG      No paramiters
@ENDNODE


@NODE SaveConfig
@{U}Save Config@{UU}

	This menu item will write the S:CallerID.cfg file. This is
	something you would need to do once you move any of the
	windows if you plan on having them stay where you put them.
	If you don't save them, they will return to their old
	locations when you start the program the next time or when
	you use the @{" Load Config " link LoadConfig} menu item.


	@{fg shine}@{U}ARexx Command@{UU}@{fg text}
	SAVECFG      No paramiters
@ENDNODE


@NODE Config
@{U}Configure@{UU}

	This menu item will start your favorite text editor with
	the @" S:CallerID.cfg " link Configuration} file loaded up. 
	You can then make your changes and save them.
	
	After saving, be sure to use the @{" Load Config " link LoadConfig} menu item.


	@{fg shine}@{U}ARexx Command@{UU}@{fg text}
	CONFIG       No paramiters
@ENDNODE


@NODE TrimHist
@{U}Trim History@{UU}

	This menu item will remove any duplicate entries in the
	history window/file. It will also remove any entry without
	a phone number attached. The only exception is the most
	current call. That one is always left alone so you can see
	when the very last call came in.
	
	Normaly, GS CallerID will keep every call in the order they
	come in. But you may get a large number of calls in your
	history buffer and want to keep track of most of them but
	make room for new ones. This will let you do that.
	
	If the history file fills up, the oldest call will be over
	written by the new call. So there is no need to worry about
	the file over filling.


	@{fg shine}@{U}ARexx Command@{UU}@{fg text}
	TRIM       No paramiters
@ENDNODE


@NODE QuitHist
@{U}Quit CallerID@{UU}

	DUHHHHH!!!!
	
	This will close the program and all files and all windows.
	
	Game over. You are done.


	@{fg shine}@{U}ARexx Command@{UU}@{fg text}
	QUIT       No paramiters
@ENDNODE


@NODE AddBB
@{U}Add Black Book Entry@{UU}

	This simply adds a new entry to the end of your
	@{" Black Book " link BlackBook} file. You can edit the phone number
	and all the other information to fit your needs.
	
	As new calls come in, they are also added automatically
	to the @{" Black Book " link BlackBook}.


	@{fg shine}@{U}ARexx Command@{UU}@{fg text}
	ADD       No paramiters
	          Returns an intiger showing the new entry's number
	          (returns 0 of no record was added)
@ENDNODE


@NODE KillBB
@{U}Kill/Delete A Black Book Entry@{UU}

	This will delete the currently active entry in the @{" Black Book " link BlackBook}.
	
	You will be given a chance to change your mind just before
	the entry is deleted. But once removed, it is gone and can't
	be recovered.


	@{fg shine}@{U}ARexx Command@{UU}@{fg text}
	KILL #     Replace # with the entry number to delete
@ENDNODE


@NODE SortBB
@{U}Sort The Black Book@{UU}

	This will sort all the entries in the @{" Black Book " link BlackBook}.
	
	You will be given the choice between sorting by the
	name or phone number. The name is sorted as a solid string.
	I have no good way to determine what word is the first name
	or last name. Some people will list things LAST, FIRST and
	others will list them as FIRST LAST. And then what do you do
	when it is a business name or several people at the same
	phone number.


	@{fg shine}@{U}ARexx Command@{UU}@{fg text}
	SORT 0       Ask the user if he/she wants to sort then SORT 1
	SORT 1       Ask to sort by the NAME or PHONE NUMBER
	SORT 2       Sort by the NAME (don't ask user)
	SORT 3       Sort by the PHONE NUMBER (don't ask user)
@ENDNODE


@NODE QuitBB
@{U}Quit The Black Book@{UU}

	DUHHHHH!!!!
	
	This will close the @{" Black Book " link BlackBook} portion of the
	CallerID program. The main portion of the program will
	continue to run.


	@{fg shine}@{U}ARexx Command@{UU}@{fg text}
	CLOSEBB      No paramiters
@ENDNODE


@NODE 3Buttons
@{U}History Window Three Buttons@{UU}

There are 3 buttons on the history window. Here is how they work...

	1) The CB button. This will allow you to call the number
	   currently displayed in the history window. This works
	   just like the @{" DIAL BUTTON " link DialButton} in the @{" Black Book " link BlackBook}.
	
	2) The DND button. This one is rather rude. But there may
	   be a time where you don't want to be bothered by anyone.
	   The incoming call will be logged into the history buffer
	   and the caller will get the CLICK action. That is the
	   modem will pick up the phone then hang up. How rude!
	
	3) The FS button. This will free the serial port. Then any
	   other program can use the modem without being bothered by
	   GS CallerID. The modem will be reset once you release this
	   switch.
@ENDNODE


@NODE BlackBook
@{U}BlackBook@{UU}

First! There are a couple ways to get into the Black Book. All of them 
start by activating the incoming call window. Simply click on the window 
and it will pop open if it isn't already open. Then you have three ways 
you can open the Black Book....

	1) Select the menu item Black Book.

	2) Press the Right Amiga button and the B key at the same time.

	3) Just press the B key all by itself
	   (or with any other key for that matter)

I wanted it to be really easy to get into the Black Book so I have used a 
couple quick options. Use the one you like the most. I like the B key myself. 

Once the Black Book opens, the incoming call/history window will jump back 
to stand by mode. This gets it out of your way. Don't worry, any incoming 
calls will be identified while you are using the Black Book. I wouldn't want 
you to miss a call!

The Black Book window is divided into three parts...

	1) The top of the Black Book window looks much like the 
	   incoming call/history window. The date, number of calls, 
	   and time are posted there. You can't edit these fields. 
	   There is no real reason to do so. If something really bad 
	   happens and the data is damaged, you probably need to 
	   delete the entire file any way.

	2) The bottom of the window is used for moving around in the 
	   Black Book. This is much like the way it is done in the 
	   incoming call/history window. You can use the arrow keys 
	   to jump from entry to entry. But I wanted you to have 
	   more control here. So, you may also key in any entry 
	   number in the numeric box located at the bottom left of 
	   the window. OR you can drag (or click) the slider gadget 
	   to get to where you want to be. I wanted you to have 
	   several options. You will also find a @{" DIAL BUTTON " link DialButton} and
	   @{" FIND BUTTON " link FindButton} in this section.

	3) The middle of the window is the really important part. 
	   At least it is to me. This is where you are allowed to 
	   edit the caller's information. Things like their name, 
	   address, a note, their action.

	   @{fg fill}NOTE:@{fg text} Any time you make a change to an entry in the
	         Black Book, you need to press TAB or ENTER to
	         save the change. As soon as you press TAB or
	         ENTER, the change is stored to the disk.


	   Although I have allowed you to edit the caller's phone 
	   number, it is not a good idea unless that caller has 
	   really changed their phone number. Because if they call,
	   and the number you have entered is not identical to the 
	   one that comes in through the Caller ID message from the 
	   modem, a new entry will be created in the Black Book with
	   their real number. I only added this ability because I wouldn't 
	   want to retype all the information just because someone 
	   changed their phone number.

	   Next to the phone number, you will see a @{" LOCAL/LD " link LOCAL} button.
	   Use this to set the phone number type.

	   Right under the phone number is the name field. You are 
	   allowed up to 40 characters in this field. That is more 
	   than enough for almost any name (or company name) you 
	   might come across. if not, too bad, abbreviate.

	   Then phone number and name field are special fields and 
	   are used as such so it is only possible to put what are 
	   deemed valid phone numbers in the phone number slot. And 
	   it is to you advantage to only put names in the name slot. 
	   But that one is up to you I guess.

	   The next two lines are intended for the address. You can 
	   of course put any text you like in here because these 
	   fields are not used for anything other than display 
	   purposes at this time. That may change in the future so 
	   it is a good idea if you can to follow the designations. 
	   The street address (or mailing address) goes on the 1st 
	   of the two lines and the City, State, Zip on the next. 
	   But again, this is really up to you. I am only suggesting 
	   at this point. You are again limited to 40 characters on 
	   each of these lines.

	   The next line down is the NOTE line. This is really where 
	   your note should go. You have up to 40 characters to work 
	   with. It isn't a lot of room for a note to some people, 
	   but this is to keep the data base small. If you need lots 
	   of room, that may be vailable through external programs at 
	   a later time.

	   The last field you can type in is the ACTION line. Here 
	   you have 127 characters of space. I offer so much room 
	   because often programs require parameters. Full paths may 
	   also be required. 127 characters should be enough. If not, 
	   you may need to make an assignment to shorten up the path 
	   or call a script file. If you leave this blank, the default 
	   action listed in the config file will be executed.

	   There is a click gadget at the bottom. by default, this 
	   will read "Do Nothing". This is what the modem should do
	   when a call comes in for this person. You have 5 options
	   for this gadget at this time.

		1) Do Nothing
		   This is the default. The modem doesn't to 
		   anything. It just sits there and listens to 
		   the modem for the next call.

		2) CLICK
		   This is where the modem answers with no 
		   tone and then hangs up. This is rude but
		   for those people who call over and over even
		   when you tell them not to, this is a great 
		   way to deal with them.

		3) BUZZ
		   This is even more rude than CLICK. The modem
		   will answer, buzz in the caller's ear, then 
		   hang up. This will really stop people from 
		   calling you.

		4) Go to Shared mode, Do Action, Reset Modem
		   This is great for answering the modem with 
		   another program such as a BBS or FAX program. 
		   You have GS CallerID set the serial port into 
		   shared mode then after the action returns 
		   control, it resets the modem. Even if you 
		   have GS CallerID in shared mode is the default 
		   in the config file, this is the most common 
		   way to access other programs and give out 
		   control for the duration of a call.

	@{fg fill}NOTE:@{fg text} The incoming call window WILL NOT close while the 
	      external program has control of the modem.

		5) Close the port, Do Action, Open port
		   This is for those extreme programs that won't 
		   accept shared mode. It works just like mode 4 
		   but completely closes the serial port then 
		   re-opens it once control is returned.

You will want to keep in mind that when you give control to another 
program, there is about a 1 or 2 second delay after GS CallerID gets 
control back before the modem is reset. Then another 1 or 2 seconds 
while the modem is being reset. This shouldn't effect your incoming 
calls but it could if the timing of the next incoming call is just right.

Through the use of the menu, you have the ability to add and delete 
records. You can of course use the menu short cut keys. I think the 
idea of adding and deleting is simple enough I don't need to go in 
to any detail about it.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Expectation
@{U}Expectation@{UU}

Here are a few things that you can look forward to in the up coming 
versions of this program. I simply wanted to get this working version 
out to the public in a timely manner so I have decided to save these 
things for the next time around.

   1) A GUI for the configuration file (soon)

   2) Multi line support for those with more than one phone line

   3) More ARexx scripts

   4) More preconfiguration choices for the installer.

   The last two may never come off the list as I can always keep
   adding scrips and upgrading the preconfigurations as long as
   there are new modems being built and new ideas for scripts.


I am of course open to suggestions on other things that could be done 
with this program. 

I am also willing to add any @{" ARexx " link ARexx} @{" script " link Scripts} you design to my archive if
they are well written including some documentations (which can be in
the script if you decide that is easier)

@{" Contact Me " link Contact}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Registration
@{U}Registration@{UU}

This program is SHAREWARE... This means you can test it out before paying 
for it. It is not free. Supporting the shareware programmer can only help 
you get the software you want at a reasonable price.

I don't like to make programs unusable. So all the features are turned on 
accept for the ability to load a configuration file. This in turn limits 
the number of calls that are stored in the history file and @{" Black Book " link BlackBook} 
file. It also makes it impossible to save the locations or look of the 
windows. You are stuck with the defaults. BUT you do get a good feel for 
all the program can do. 

Once you register, you will receive a @{" KEY FILE " link KEY} that unlocks all the 
configuration file and you can play with all the little settings you want. 
You will receive FREE upgrades forever! I generally don't require paid 
upgrading to any of my software. Something incredible would have to happen 
for me to change this policy. I don't send out upgrades unless you are on 
one of my InterNet mailing lists for them. But the new shareware versions 
that come out will use the same key file as V1.0 and if for some reason I 
need to change the key file, I usually offer free key upgrades to 
registered users.

GS CallerID is what I would class as a valuable program. In this version 
its applications are some what limited but once the few additions that I 
already have on the drawing board are added, the value explodes. The 
current and future value of this program along with the increasing number 
of cities that are making CallerID available to their residents brings me 
to my requested price of $20.00 for this program. I hope you see enough 
value in what I have delivered at this point and trust me enough to 
continue developing (which I will because even if you don't want the 
features, I do) to see that this is a fair and reasonable price to ask.

All you need to do is fill in the registration form below, throw in your 
money, and I will get you your key file and the most current version of 
the program as quickly as possible. In most cases, I ship the next day 
after receiving the registration fee and form.


	@{" View Registratoin Form " SYSTEM "more Registration"}	@{" Print Registratoin Form " SYSTEM "Type >PRT: Registration"}

@ENDNODE

@NODE DEVICE
@{U}DEVICE@{UU}

	This is the name of  the serial device you use. By default, 
	this will be set to "serial.device" but it can be any valid 
	serial device driver. The GVP I/O card uses gvpser.device and 
	the MultiFace II card uses duart.device.
@ENDNODE


@NODE UNIT
@{U}UNIT@{UU}

	This is the serial port unit device. By default this is set 
	to 0 (zero) but again can be any valid unit number on your 
	system. Just make sure you specify the correct device and unit 
	or the program won't be able to find your modem.
@ENDNODE


@NODE BAUD
@{U}BAUD@{UU}

	The speed at which the computer will talk to the modem. You 
	can make this any valid baud rate from 9600 baud to 115200 
	baud as long as the serial device you specified and the modem 
	both support that speed. By default, this set to 9600. I have 
	found that although I can get Caller ID to work at speeds lower 
	than 9600, it is not reliable. The information coming from the 
	modem often takes too long and is destroyed by the next in 
	coming ring. So 9600 baud is the minimum value.
@ENDNODE


@NODE SHARED
@{U}SHARED@{UU}

	This tells the GS CallerID to open the serial port in shared 
	mode all the time. You can only enter 0 (zero) or 1 (one) for 
	this field. Any non-zero value will be taken as a one. 
	Shared mode = 1, non-shared mode = 0. By default the serial 
	port is not opened in shared mode. This is really the best way 
	to run the program unless you have some special need.
@ENDNODE


@NODE BACKUP
@{U}BACKUP@{UU}

	@{fg shine}@{U}Config File@{UU}@{fg text}
	This option tells GS CallerID to make a backup of the
	@{" Black Book " link BlackBook} file any time the program is started, an entry
	is deleted, or the file is sorted.
	
	
	@{fg shine}@{U}ARexx Command@{UU}@{fg text}
	BACKUP -1   Read the backup status flag.
	BACKUP 0    Make no backups starting now.
	BACKUP 1    Make backups starting now.
	BACKUP 2    Make a backup RIGHT NOW but don't
	            alter the current setting.
@ENDNODE


@NODE FixClock
@{U}FIXCLOCK@{UU}

	This is a nifty little item that will reset your batter backedup
	clock and the system time/date if they are off from the time/date
	supplied by the phone company.
	
	This will not work on all systems. At this time I have used a
	very simple method of resetting this and it only works with systems
	that have battery backedup clocks. Sorry, I may change this later.
	
	You can set this option to any value from 2-10 if you want to 
	have the time altered. Or if you don't want to use this function,
	you can set the option to 0 (zero) and the time will never be
	altered. Do this if you have no clock or if you have any trouble.
	
	The number you specify (2-10) is the number of minutes that the
	system clock must be off before any alterations are made.
	
	Any value out of range will of course be corrected automatically.
	
	
	Default:       FIXCLOCK = 3;

		(if the system clock is off by 3 minutes or more
		 from the time/date supplied by the phone company,
		 the system clock will be reset to the phone
		 company's time/date settings)
		 

@ENDNODE


@NODE RESET
@{U}RESET@{UU}

	This is the modem command that is used to cause a full modem 
	reset. By default, this is ATZ and should stay that way unless 
	you have special needs.
@ENDNODE


@NODE CID
@{U}CID@{UU}

	This is the modem command that turn the caller ID on for your 
	modem. By default the command is AT#CID=2 and if you are running 
	a Supra modem or compatible (most are) this will do just fine. 
	If this doesn't work for you, you will need to check your modem 
	manual for help.
	
	There are so many ways for modems to filter the caller ID info,
	I found it much much easier to simply grab the RAW data and decode
	it myself. All of the modems I have tested provide the raw data
	in the same format. A long line of HEX characters.
	
	Because some modems don't offer RAW mode, you can use the standard
	text mode if you prefer. Please take a look at these features...
	
	@{" CIDDATE " link CIDDATE}  @{" CIDTIME " link CIDTIME}  @{" CIDNMBR " link CIDNMBR}  @{" CIDNAME " link CIDNAME}  @{" CIDMODE " link CIDMODE}
	
	If you are going to be using CallerID with a FAX program or a BBS
	or any other data system that shares the line with the CallerID
	program, you should check out the @{" FAX/DATA " link FAXDATA} information.
@ENDNODE


@NODE CIDDATE
@{U}CIDDATE@{UU}

	This is the text that the modem returns just before the date
	is seen.
	
	If your modem sends this...
	
		DATE: 1021
		TIME: 2132
		NUMBER: 5033997518
		NAME: SCHWORAK GLENN
	
	...your entry should be this...
	
		CIDDATE = DATE:
		          ^^^^^ this is the KEY!!!!

	@{fg fill}NOTE:@{fg text} If your modem doesn't supply the date of the call, the
	      system date will be used.
@ENDNODE




@NODE CIDTIME
@{U}CIDTIME@{UU}

	This is the text that the modem returns just before the time
	is seen.
	
	If your modem sends this...
	
		DATE: 1021
		TIME: 2132
		NUMBER: 5033997518
		NAME: SCHWORAK GLENN
	
	...your entry should be this...
	
		CIDTIME = TIME:
		          ^^^^^ this is the KEY!!!!

	@{fg fill}NOTE:@{fg text} If your modem doesn't supply the time of the call, the
	      system time will be used.
@ENDNODE




@NODE CIDNMBR
@{U}CIDNMBR@{UU}

	This is the text that the modem returns just before the phone
	number is seen.
	
	If your modem sends this...
	
		DATE: 1021
		TIME: 2132
		NUMBER: 5033997518
		NAME: SCHWORAK GLENN
	
	...your entry should be this...
	
		CIDDATE = NUMBER:
		          ^^^^^^^ this is the KEY!!!!

@ENDNODE




@NODE CIDNAME
@{U}CIDNAME@{UU}

	This is the text that the modem returns just before the caller's
	name is seen.
	
	If your modem sends this...
	
		DATE: 1021
		TIME: 2132
		NUMBER: 5033997518
		NAME: SCHWORAK GLENN
	
	...your entry should be this...
	
		CIDDATE = NAME:
		          ^^^^^ this is the KEY!!!!

@ENDNODE




@NODE CIDMODE
@{U}CIDMODE@{UU}

	This is VERY IMPORTANT to get right!
	
	CIDMODE = 0     <--- If you set the @{" CID " link CID} to RAW mode

	CIDMODE = 1     <--- If the DATE is output last

	CIDMODE = 2     <--- If the TIME is output last

	CIDMODE = 3     <--- If the PHONE NUMBER is output last

	CIDMODE = 4     <--- If the CALLER NAME is output last
	
	I have found that most modems send the caller name last
	when displaying the incoming call information. But some
	modems change the order. Therefore it is important that
	you tell GS CallerID how to process the incoming data.
@ENDNODE


@NODE OFFHOOK
@{U}OFFHOOK@{UU}

	This is the command that will cause the modem to answer the 
	phone but make no noise. Simply take the phone off the hook. 
	It is used when you want GS CallerID to block phone calls for 
	you. The phone is answered then hung up again. By default this
	is ATH1 and works for most modems.
@ENDNODE


@NODE ONHOOK
@{U}ONHOOK@{UU}

	This is the command that hangs up the phone. Used after the 
	OFFHOOK or TONEANSWER commands are used. By default this is 
	ATH0 and works for most modems.
@ENDNODE


@NODE TONEANSWER
@{U}TONEANSWER@{UU}

	This is the command that will cause the modem to answer the 
	phone and buzz in the caller's ear. This is a really rude thing 
	to do so I recommend you only use it on people who are really 
	really annoying and won't stop bothering you. By default
	the command is ATA and works on most modems.
@ENDNODE


@NODE DIAL
@{U}DIAL@{UU}

	This is the command that is sent to the modem to cause it to
	dial out. You need to place a  in the string where you want
	the phone number placed. The default is ATDT 
	
	This default causes the phone number to be inserted, dialed,
	then the modem is returned to the command mode. For example,
	the number 5033997518 would be insterted into the string to 
	prodice....
	
		ATDT 3997518             (if the number is local)
	
	If the number is not local to you, you need to set the @{" LOCAL/LD " link LOCAL}
	button in the @{" Black Book " link BlackBook} to cause the number to be dialed 
	properly when you click the @{" DIAL BUTTON " link DialButton}.
@ENDNODE


@NODE DEFDIAL
@{U}Default Dial Mode@{UU}

	By default, the system will assume any new phone number that is
	added to the @{" Black Book " link BlackBook} file is a LOCAL number.
		
	This could be a problem for people out side of the US or people
	who get more long distence calls than local calls. So to remidy this
	I have added a default dialing mode to the configuration file.
	
	DEFDIAL = 0       Local       (default - dial 7 digits only)

	DEFDIAL = 1       LD 1        (Dial 1 and the 7 digit number)

	DEFDIAL = 2       LD 1+Area   (Dial 1 and the entire number)
	
	DEFDIAL = 3       AS IS       (Dial all digits AS IS)
	
	DEFDIAL = 4       X-Index     @{B}(NEVER NEVER USE THIS AS A DEFDIAL)@{UB}

	You can get more information on these modes by looking at the
	@{" LOCAL " link local} button settings for the @{" Black Book " link BlackBook}.
@ENDNODE


@NODE BBONLY
@{U}Black Book Only mode@{UU}

	By default, BBONLY is set to 0 (zero) or off mode. This program is
	designed to be a CallerID program. But some people may want to use
	the @{" Black Book " link BlackBook} only and not mess with CallerID. So I have added in
	this ability. If you set BBONLY = 1 in your configuration file,
	the serial port will never be opened. And by selecting the CallerID
	window, a couple seconds later the @{" Black Book " link BlackBook} will automatically
	open.
	
	Valid values: 0 or 1     (for off or on)
	
@ENDNODE


@NODE FAXDATA
@{U}FAX/DATA recognition@{UU}

	Lets assume you want to run your CallerID program on the same
	line you run a BBS or FAX program. OR BOTH!

	The assumption here is that CallerID will be answering the mode
	and process the connection. The connect message will be read then
	control will be passed to another program.
	
	But how do you get all of these things to work together. CallerID
	must be first or it won't get the phone number information.
	
	Well, this is simple if you set the proper values into the
	@{" CID " link CID}, @{" FAX " link FAX}, @{" FAXCMD " link FAXCMD}, @{" CONNECT " link connect}, and @{" CONNECTCMD " link CONNECTCMD}
	lines.
	
	You will really need to know a bit about your BBS/FAX software 
	and your modem to configure these settings properly. I only specialize
	in SupraFAX and even then it is a little tricky. There is some scripts
	you will need to write. Check the included scripts and see if you can
	get some ideas from what is there.
	
	If you want to share the CallerID line between VOICE and FAX/DATA
	connections, then that is different. You need to use the @{" SILENT " link SILENT}
	and @{" SILENTCMD " link SILENTCMD} settings to make that work.
@ENDNODE


@NODE FAX
@{U}FAX recognition@{UU}

	This is the text your modem sends out when a FAX connection
	is detected.
	
	Usualy this would be "FAX" or "+FCON" and is what the Supra
	sends out.
	
	By default, this field is blank. A blank entry will cause
	this feature to be turned off.
	
	If this command is seen coming from the modem then the
	@{" FAXCMD " link FAXCMD} command is executed if it is filled in.
@ENDNODE


@NODE FAXCMD
@{U}The FAX command@{UU}

	This command will be executed if the @{" FAX " link FAX} command
	comes in from the modem.
	
	This command will have "RUN <>NIL:" added to the start of the line
	to cause it to be run in background. This should also be an ARexx
	script or DOS script with inline ARexx commands at the end. To cause
	CallerID to be reset. This is because CallerID doesn't really care
	that the modem has connected. It lets the command take control at
	this point and won't mess with the modem again until it is told to.
	
	The serial port is thrown into SHARED mode just before running
	this command. When you do a reset, the normal state of the serial
	port will be restored as described by the @{" SHARED " link SHARED} line in
	the config file.
	
	Normally, if you use an ARexx script, you would end your script
	with this little routine...
	
		Address CID
		Serial Close
		Shell Command "Wait 1"
		Serial Open
		Shell Command "Wait 1"
		Serial Reset
		exit
	
	This may seem a bit odd, but it ensures that the modem gets
	completely reset.
@ENDNODE


@NODE CONNECT
@{U}Data Connections@{UU}

	This is the message the modem sends out when a DATA connection
	is detected.
	
	Usualy this would be set to CONNECT with no baud specification.
	
	The assumption is the serial port is locked to a given baud rate.
	If your modem doesn't do that, tuff. I am not messing with that
	can of worms. Pay the extra ten bucks to get a real modem.
	
	By default, this field is blank. A blank entry will cause
	this feature to be turned off.
	
	If this command is seen coming from the modem then the
	@{" CONNECTCMD " link CONNECTCMD} command is executed if it is filled in.
	
@ENDNODE


@NODE CONNECTCMD
@{U}The CONNECT command@{UU}

	This command will be executed if the @{" CONNECT " link CONNECT} command
	comes in from the modem.
	
	This command will have "RUN <>NIL:" added to the start of the line
	to cause it to be run in background. This should also be an ARexx
	script or DOS script with inline ARexx commands at the end. To cause
	CallerID to be reset. This is because CallerID doesn't really care
	that the modem has connected. It lets the command take control at
	this point and won't mess with the modem again until it is told to.
	
	The serial port is thrown into SHARED mode just before running
	this command. When you do a reset, the normal state of the serial
	port will be restored as described by the @{" SHARED " link SHARED} line in
	the config file.
	
	Normally, if you use an ARexx script, you would end your script
	with this little routine...
	
		Address CID
		Serial Close
		Shell Command "Wait 1"
		Serial Open
		Shell Command "Wait 1"
		Serial Reset
		exit
	
	This may seem a bit odd, but it ensures that the modem gets
	completely reset.
@ENDNODE


@NODE SILENT
@{U}Silent Answer@{UU}

	Many new modems offer the ability to Silent Answer the phone line.
	
	Basically, what this does is the modem hears the ring, listens
	for a moment (picks up the CallerID info if you have it turned on)
	then hangs up. This special listen doesn't stop the phone from
	ringing. You may answer the phone, or let the answering machine
	get it. The modem will again listen for a moment. If it hears
	a FAX signal (or a DATA signal on some morems) a special set of
	"FAST RINGS" are sent out by the mode to the CallerID program.
	
	These rings come in one after another in about 1 second gaps.
	This is about 5 times faster than normal rings. The CallerID
	program will recognize these rings to be different from the
	normal ones. And the @{" SILENTCMD " link SILENTCMD} command will be
	executed.
	
	In the CONFIG file, you need to set the number of "FAST RINGS"
	to be detected before the Silent Answer command should be run.
	
	By default, this would be set to 0 (zero) which turns Silent
	Answer off completely. 
	
	For best results, you will want to set this between 5 and 9.
	Even though values from 1-9 will cause the command to work, it
	may result in false starts if you set it too low.
	
		IE: SILENT = 0    <--- No Silent Answer
		    SILENT = 5    <--- Run command after 5 FAST RINGS
	
	You should note that when you use this mode, you probaly won't
	be running a BBS on the same line as most people don't like to,
	don't know how, or simply can't cause their modems to send the
	connection tones the Silent Answer mode is going to be listening
	for when it is active. And many modems won't listen for DATA
	tones anyway. Usualy it is FAX only that is recognized. Check
	your modem manual for more info on Silent Answering.
	
	
	If you need to have the CallerID program answer the phone line
	and then determine if this is a FAX or DATA call, you need to
	look at the @{" FAX/DATA " link FAXDATA} section.


NOTE: Some modems don't handle silent answer very well. They will
      get confused by some voices on the line and will respond
      as if a computer tone has been detected. This can be fixed
      through configurations for your modem in most cases.
      This IS NOT a bug in CallerID. CallerID doesn't do the detection!
@ENDNODE


@NODE SILENTCMD
@{U}The Silent Answer command@{UU}

	This command is executed when you use the @{" SILENT " link SILENT} answer
	mode on your modem (if it has one that is). When the modem hears
	a FAX/DATA signal to CallerID.

	This command will have "RUN <>NIL:" added to the start of the line
	to cause it to be run in background. This should also be an ARexx
	script or DOS script with inline ARexx commands at the end. To cause
	CallerID to be reset. This is because CallerID doesn't really care
	that the modem has connected. It lets the command take control at
	this point and won't mess with the modem again until it is told to.
	
	The serial port is thrown into SHARED mode just before running
	this command. When you do a reset, the normal state of the serial
	port will be restored as described by the @{" SHARED " link SHARED} line in
	the config file.
	
	Normally, if you use an ARexx script, you would end your script
	with this little routine...
	
		Address CID
		Serial Close
		Shell Command "Wait 1"
		Serial Open
		Shell Command "Wait 1"
		Serial Reset
		exit
	
	This may seem a bit odd, but it ensures that the modem gets
	completely reset.
@ENDNODE


@NODE SLOWMODEM
@{U}SLOWMODEM@{UU}

	This will cause a delay when sending commands to the modem. By 
	default this value is 1 (one) but you can use any number from 
	0 (zero) to 3 (three). I would recommend starting with the 
	lowest value and if you have problems increase the value one at 
	a time until the errors go away.
@ENDNODE


@NODE ACTION
@{U}ACTION@{UU}

	AAAhhhhh... Here is where the fun starts! This is the CLI 
	command that is executed when any incoming call comes in. By 
	default, no action is preformed. If you want, you can 
	specify alternative actions in the @{" Black Book " link BlackBook} for each caller. 
	But if no alternative action exists in the @{" Black Book " link BlackBook}, this default 
	action will be used.
	
	If you place a %s in the action line, the caller's name
	is inserted at that point.
@ENDNODE


@NODE PATH
@{U}PATH@{UU}

	This is the path to the CallerID.BlackBook and CallerID.History 
	files. By default, this is the S: directory. You can place these 
	files in any valid directory you want and then set this entry to 
	point to that directory. If you change the path, it is best to do 
	so while GS CallerID is not running. You won't be able to move the 
	files while it is.
@ENDNODE


@NODE DEBUG
@{U}DEBUG@{UU}

	@{fg shine}@{U}Config File@{UU}@{fg text}
	Being that there may be bugs or problems, I have left in some
	of the debug code for now. If you are experiencing problems, 
	simply set this entry to a value of 1 (one) and run the program 
	again or reload the configuration file. If you want help from 
	me, you will need to use a CLI session to start the CallerID 
	program and redirect the output to a file and then send me the 
	file so I can figure out where the problem is. This can be done 
	with the command CallerID >t:CID.log and after you are done 
	running the program or have encountered your problem, you simple 
	exit the program and Email or send me the CID.log file with a 
	description of your problem. The valid settings for this entry are 
	0 (zero for no debug) to 3 (three for max debug). 
	By default, the debug mode is set to 0 (zero).
	
	@{fg shine}@{U}ARexx Command@{UU}@{fg text}
	DEBUG #      Replace the # with a number 0 - 3
	
		
	@{fg fill}NOTE:@{fg text} While in debug mode, you can hault the program by pressing
	      <CONTROL>C when the debug window is the active window. A
	      full clean up should take place and you can go on your way.
@ENDNODE


@NODE X
@{U}X@{UU}

	Only used if you have @{" register " link Registration}.

	The X location on the screen of the upper left hand corner of 
	the caller ID window when a call comes in. (This is the left 
	to right position) This is easy to set graphically! Simply move 
	the window to where you want it to be then save the configuration
	to disk. The window defaults to the upper left corner of the 
	screen.
@ENDNODE


@NODE Y
@{U}Y@{UU}

	Only used if you have @{" registered " link Registration}.

	The Y location on the screen of the upper left hand corner of 
	the caller ID window when a call comes in. (This is the top to 
	bottom position) This is easy to set graphically! Simply move 
	the window to where you want it to be then save the configuration
	to disk. The window defaults to the upper left corner of the 
	screen.
@ENDNODE


@NODE SMALLX
@{U}SMALLX@{UU}

	The X location on the screen of the upper left hand corner of 
	the caller ID window when the program is in stand by mode. 
	(This is the left to right position) This is easy to set 
	graphically! Simply move the window to where you want it to be 
	then save the configuration to disk. The window defaults to the 
	upper left corner of the screen.
@ENDNODE


@NODE SMALLY
@{U}SMALLY@{UU}

	The Y location on the screen of the upper left hand corner of the 
	caller ID window when the program is in stand by mode. (This is 
	the top to bottom position) This is easy to set graphically! 
	Simply move the window to where you want it to be then 
	save the configuration to disk. The window defaults to the upper 
	left corner of the screen.
@ENDNODE


@NODE BBX
@{U}BBX@{UU}

	Only used if you have @{" registered " link Registration}.

	The X location on the screen of the upper left hand corner of 
	the caller @{" Black Book " link BlackBook} window when open. (This is the left to 
	right position) This is easy to set graphically! Simply move 
	the window to where you want it to be then save the configuration
	to disk. The window defaults to the upper left corner of the 
	screen.
@ENDNODE


@NODE BBY
@{U}BBY@{UU}

	Only used if you have @{" registered " link Registration}.

	The Y location on the screen of the upper left hand corner of 
	the caller @{" Black Book " link BlackBook} window when open. (This is the top to 
	bottom position) This is easy to set graphically! Simply move 
	the window to where you want it to be then save the configuration
	to disk. The window defaults to the upper left corner of the 
	screen.
@ENDNODE


@NODE BACKGROUND
@{U}BACKGROUND@{UU}

	This is the pen number that you want used for the background on 
	the incoming call window. By default, this is set to 3 under the 
	assumption you are only running a 4 color WorkBench. But who 
	really does that any more? You can really set this to any value you 
	want but only valid pen numbers will actually function properly.
@ENDNODE


@NODE BBBACKGROUND
@{U}BBBACKGROUND@{UU}

	This is the pen number that you want used for the background on 
	the @{" Black Book " link BlackBook} window. By default, this is set to 3 under the 
	assumption you are only running a 4 color WorkBench. But who really 
	does that any more? You can really set this to any value you want 
	but only valid pen numbers will actually function properly.
@ENDNODE


@NODE WARNBACKGROUND
@{U}WARNBACKGROUND@{UU}

	This is the pen number that you want used for the background on 
	the WARNING window. By default, this is set to 0 under the 
	assumption you are only running a 4 color WorkBench. But who really 
	does that any more? You can really set this to any value you want 
	but only valid pen numbers will actually function properly. I like 
	to use RED for this one!!!
@ENDNODE


@NODE TEXTCOLOR
@{U}TEXTCOLOR@{UU}

	You get to choose the main color of the text displayed in the 
	various windows. (sorry, all text must be the same color at this 
	time). By default, this uses the #2 pen (usually white) but like 
	with the other colors, you can set it to any value you like as long 
	as the screen supports it.
@ENDNODE


@NODE SHADOWCOLOR
@{U}SHADOWCOLOR@{UU}

	Much of the text displayed in the various windows is given the 
	look of depth by drawing it twice! Once in the shadow color 
	(usually black or dark gray) and once in the text color slightly 
	off set to make it look like it is lifted off the screen. This is 
	set to 1 (usually black) by default.
@ENDNODE


@NODE SECONDS
@{U}SECONDS@{UU}

	Only used if you have @{" registered " link Registration}.

	This is the number of seconds you want the incoming call window 
	to stay open before automatically shrinking back to the stand by 
	mode. By default this is 15 seconds but I find that 8 to 10 
	actually works well for me. Notice, if you have selected
	the incoming call window this value is not used. As soon as you 
	unselect the window it jumps right to stand by mode.
@ENDNODE


@NODE HISTORY
@{U}HISTORY@{UU}

	Only used if you have @{" registered " link Registration}.

	This is the number of calls you want to keep track of in your 
	review history file. By default this is set to 4 calls. It 
	can't be set any lower than 3 calls either. Why? Because I said 
	so. There is no upper limit, but I find that 100 calls is more
	that enough. I generally don't go back that far. Usually only 
	20-30 calls. But what the heck. If you want to scroll back 
	10,000 calls in history, one at a time, go for it! The history 
	file is of FIXED size so once it is set, it won't grow/shrink 
	unless you reset it later.
@ENDNODE


@NODE BBMAX
@{U}BBMAX@{UU}

	Only used if you have @{" registered " link Registration}.

	This is the maximum number of  names/numbers you want to keep 
	track of in your @{" Black Book " link BlackBook}. By default, this is set to 6 
	entries. But I am sure you will want to change that. If you set 
	this entry to 0 (zero) there is no limit on the size of the 
	@{" Black Book " link BlackBook}. This file will grow (never shrink unless you delete 
	it) as entries are added.
@ENDNODE


@NODE SHOWTIME
@{U}SHOWTIME@{UU}

	You can opt to have the GS CallerID program display the time 
	of day in the window title bar. This is a great way to conserve 
	desk space. No need to run a clock and the CallerID program just 
	to see the time. GS CallerID is running so why not have it show 
	the time. By default, this is set to 0 (zero no time) but you 
	can set it to 1 (one) if you want to see the time.

	See @{" ShowDate " link ShowDate} too.
@ENDNODE


@NODE SHOWDATE
@{U}SHOWDATE@{UU}

	You can opt to have the GS CallerID program display the current
	date in the window title bar. This is a great way to conserve 
	desk space. No need to run a date program and GS CallerID just 
	to see the date. GS CallerID is running so why not have it show 
	the date. By default, this is set to 0 (zero no time) but you 
	can set it to 1 (one) if you want to see the date.
	
	See @{" ShowTime " link ShowTime} too.
@ENDNODE



@NODE Rings
@{U}FIRSTRING and MORERINGS@{UU}

	With these two configuration entries, you can have the computer
	do something each time the phone rings. 
	
	I know many people only want to know when the first ring comes
	in, so that is why there are two commands. 
	
	FIRSTRING only executes on the first ring (suprize!)
	MORERINGS only executes on the 2nd and up rings (suprize!)
	
	You may need to specify the full path to the program you want
	to run. Me, I use both commands because I want this cool zing
	sound to be played on the first and all other rings.
	
	By default, these commands are left blank. Nothing is done.
@ENDNODE

@NODE FONT
@{U}FONT@{UU}

	Only used if you have @{" registered " link Registration}.

	You can enter the name of any FIXED WIDTH 8 point font you like.
	Because the calculations of font size was more than I wanted to
	deal with at this time, I have decided to limit the font size. But
	I will leave it up to you to choose the actual font you want to
	to use. Just be sure it is the right size. If not, the program
	will revert to TOPAZ 8.
@ENDNODE


@NODE Scripts
@{U}Included ARexx Scripts@{UU}

Just for convenience, I have named all scripts that work with GS CallerID
with the extension .cid (as in Caller ID).

The installer will copy these scripts to the REXX: if you want. The originals
will be kept in the directory you install the program to unless you specify
to delete them throught the installer.


@{fg fill}NOTE:@{fg text} None of the scripts have icons until you run the installer program.
      If you would rather install the scripts and icons manualy, you can
      copy/rename the file CallerID.cid.inf1 to fit your needs. This is
      the generic icon for all CallerID ARexx scripts.

@{fg fill}NOTE 2:@{fg text} Any time you run an ARexx script from your Black Book action
        line, you should leave the modem in "DO NOTHING" mode. The
        ARexx script should take the responsibility of changing the
        serial port mode if needed. By using the other modes it is
        posible to cause a situitation where the CallerID program is
        waiting for the ARexx script to finish and the script is
        waiting for the CallerID program to wake up. This is BAD.


Currently, these scripts are installed....

@{fg shine}PrintBB.cid@{fg text}        Prints all of the entries in the @{" Black Book " link BlackBook} file.
                   The @{" Black Book " link BlackBook} is sorted by names before printing.

@{fg shine}PrintHist.cid@{fg text}      Prints all of the calls listed in the History file.
                   This list prints the newest call first and moves back in
                   history as you go down the list.

@{fg shine}BackupHist.cid@{fg text}     Copies any entries in the History with phone numbers to
                   @{" Black Book " link BlackBook} file if they are not already there. This is
                   handy if you have damaged your @{" Black Book " link BlackBook} file some how.
                   (not that I have ever done that right? hehehehe)

@{fg shine}ResizeHistory.cid@{fg text}  This script allows you to change the size of your
                   history buffer with a minimal amount of lost data.

@{fg shine}GPFaxAnswer.cid@{fg text}    A sample script showing how to get GPFax to load, answer
                   the phone, receive the FAX, hang up, then exit and return
                   control to GS CallerID. This one should only be called
                   from the ACTION command within the @{" Black Book " link BlackBook}, but you
                   might find some other use for it too.

@{fg shine}PageMe.cid@{fg text}         This script can be addapted to cause the system
                   to page you when calls come in. You can use it as your
                   Rexx:Call.cid script if you want to be paged every time
                   any call comes in. Or you can call this script from the
                   Black Book only when the people you specify call you.

@{fg shine}Announce.cid@{fg text}       If for some reason you need or want to announce
                   callers AND have a special @{" Black Book " link BlackBook} action too,
                   then this script may solve your problem. It does have a
                   little time lag since it is driven by the RING not the
                   actual call data, but it works. Take a look. You will
                   probably want to edit a couple lines before using it
                   anyway. Personalize it a bit.

@{fg shine}TestNumber.cid@{fg text}     Written By: Tim Irvin
                   This script will allow you to TYPE IN a phone number
                   and test the CallerID program's response as if
                   the number came in from the phone company.




@{fg shine}StoreDebug.cid@{B}@{fg text}     For anyone who might have trouble configuring their
                   modem or have any other problems with GS CallerID.
                   This script will help create a debug log file that
                   you can @{" send to me " link contact} and I will try to
                   help you get your system up and running.@{UB}
@ENDNODE


@NODE ARexx
@{U}The ARexx Interface@{UU}

	As you would expect, you will be able to do more with the ARexx
	interface than you can through buttons and menu items.
	
	Here is a list of the currently supported command....

	@{" LOADCFG      " link LoadConfig}	@{" SAVECFG      " link SaveConfig}	@{" CONFIG       " link Config}
	@{" OPENBB       " link OpenBB}	@{" TRIM         " link TrimHist}	@{" QUIT         " link QuitHist}
	@{" ADD          " link AddBB}	@{" KILL         " link KillBB}	@{" SORT         " link SortBB}
	@{" CLOSEBB      " link QuitBB}	@{" DEBUG        " link Debug}	@{" BUILDSCRATCH " link Scratch}
	@{" CLEARSCRATCH " link Scratch}	@{" KILLSCRATCH  " link Scratch}	@{" GETVAL       " link Val}
	@{" PUTVAL       " link Val}	@{" GETHIST      " link GetHist}	@{" GETBB        " link GetBB}
	@{" PUTBB        " link PutBB}	@{" BACKUP       " link Backup}	@{" SERIAL       " link Serial}
	@{" MODEMCDM     " link ModemCMD}	@{" MODEMREPLY   " link ModemCMD}	@{" SIMCALL      " link SimCall}
	@{" REDIAPLAY    " link Redisplay}

@{fg fill}NOTE:@{fg text} If the file Call.CID is in your REXX: directory, this script
      will be executed each time a call is detected. This is
      seperate from any ACTION you might have set up.
      @{fg fill}You need to make this yourself if you want it.@{fg text} 

@{fg fill}NOTE: 2@{fg text} If the file NewBBEntry.CID is in your REXX: directory, this script
        will be executed each time a new entry is added to your
        @{" Black Book " link BlackBook} file.
        This script is included in this archive. At least a sample.

@{fg fill}NOTE 3:@{fg text} Any time you run an ARexx script from your Black Book action
        line, you should leave the modem in "DO NOTHING" mode. The
        ARexx script should take the responsibility of changing the
        serial port mode if needed. By using the other modes it is
        posible to cause a situitation where the CallerID program is
        waiting for the ARexx script to finish and the script is
        waiting for the CallerID program to wake up. This is BAD.

@ENDNODE


@NODE ModemCMD
@{U}Direct Modem Control@{UU}    @{fg shine}@{U}ARexx Only Command@{UU}@{fg text}


Here are two commands that will help you control the modem in ways that
GS CallerID simply isn't designed to do. I am not sure what your needs
might be so I have added this with one thing in mind for myself. The
ability to control a remote modem dial out. I wanted to be able to send
an numeric message to a pager. Using the DIAL command I could come close,
but I needed some more control over the modem. These commands gave me that
control.

	ModemCMD <command string>  Will send any command to the modem allong
	                           with a <RETURN> at the end.
	
	IE: ModemCMD AT&F2         Will set my Supra to the &F2 settings
	    ModemCMD ATDT5551234;  Dials the number I am after.
	
	For the pager idea, I simply needed more delays and digits than
	DIAL command would allow (since that is expecting a number from
	the history or black book then it expects you to pick up the phone)
	
	Here is the line I used to make it work for me...
	
	    ModemCMD ATDT5551234,,,,1234567
	
	...of course the numbers are fake. The commas cause long delays.
	there is a @{" script " link scripts} included in this version that
	can be used as your REXX:CALL.CID script or as a special script in
	the @{" Black Book " link BlackBook} to cause the modem to page you
	when a call comes in. It will identify the phone number of the
	person calling. This assumes you have a numeric pager.
	
	
	
	To get some feed back from the modem, you can use the command...
	
	ModemReply    -or-    ModemReply NOW
	
	Both of these commands return infromation from the modem. The
	difference is that ModemReply by itself will only return the
	last line from the modem that ended in a new line character.
	
	If you want to know what has come from the modem even if the
	line isn't complete, you can add the NOW switch and you get
	whatever happens to be in the input buffer at the time you
	call the command.
	
	Neither of these commands cause the system to wait. If there
	is something in the buffer, you get it. If not, you get nothing.
	
	If you call ModemReply over and over, you will likely get the
	same information over and over. The reply buffer is not changed
	until a new line character is detected. 
	
	You will need to play with these a little to get the hang of them.
@ENDNODE



@NODE Serial
@{U}The Serial Port@{UU}    @{fg shine}@{U}ARexx Only Command@{UU}@{fg text}

This commands gives you a great deal of control over the serial port. You
can even cause the modem to dial out if you like.

	SERIAL  CLOSE           Close the serial port now.

	SERIAL  OPEN            Open the serial port now.
	
	SERIAL  SHARE           Put the port in SHARED mode.
	
	SERIAL  NOSHARE         Take the port out of SHARED mode.
	
	SERIAL  RESET           Reset the serial port & modem now.
	
	SERIAL  DEVICE ????     Set the serial device to ????.
	
	SERIAL  UNIT #          Set the serial unit to #.
	
	SERIAL  BAUD #####      Set the baud rate to ##### baud.
	
	SERIAL  DIAL #####      Dial the phone number #####.
	
	SERIAL  STAT            This returns a 6 word string.
	
   SERIAL  FAKE ????       Sends CallerID a fake modem message.
	
	
Values returned in the result string when you call SERIAL STAT....

	result = <device> <unit> <baud> <mode1> <mode2> <external>
	
	<device>   The serial device you are using.
	
	<unit>     The serial unit you are using.
	
	<baud>     The baud rate the port is running at.
	
	<mode1>    Is the port OPEN, CLOSED, or SLEEPING
	
	<mode2>    Is the port SHARED or MINE!
	           (MINE! means the port is not being shared)
	
	<external> Is either TRUE or FALSE. This indicates whether
	           external programs are still running or not.
@ENDNODE


@NODE SimCall
@{U}Simulated Calls@{UU}    @{fg shine}@{U}ARexx Only Command@{UU}@{fg text}


This command is wonderful for testing purposes. Also it allows you the
ability to add calls to your History buffer (and Black Book if they are
not already in there).

This was originally added for testing only, but I have also added a @{" script " link Scripts}
that will allow you to change the size of your history buffer WITHOUT 
losing any data currently in the file.


	SIMCALL [NoActions] <phone> [name]


Notice that the "NoActions" key word and the caller's name are both
optional. You must supply the phone number though.

If you supply the "NoActions" key word, the call will act as if it
just came in, but the default action, any custom option, and the
call.cid script will all be disabled.


	
Any of these three formats will work. If you don't supply a name, then
"Unknown" will be used. That is unless the number is already in the 
@{" Black Book " link BlackBook} file, in which case that name over rides any
that you might supply.
	
	
	SIMCALL 5033997518
	
	     -or-

	SIMCALL 5033997518 Glenn J. Schworak

	     -or-

	SIMCALL NoActions 5033997518 Glenn J. Schworak

@{fg fill}NOTE:@{fg text} The dashes in the phone number are not needed. They can be put in
      if you like them, but the program strips them out before processing.
      Don't put any spaces in the phone number or else part of the phone
      phone number may end up in the name field.

@ENDNODE



@NODE Scratch
@{U}The Scratch Area@{UU}    @{fg shine}@{U}ARexx Only Command@{UU}@{fg text}


The scratch area is a section of memory that is used by ARexx programs.
This memory is allocated by the @{" script " link Scripts} as needed and MUST be returned
or you risk running out of RAM.


The scratch pads are filled with the GetBB, GetHist, and PutVal
commands. You read from the scratch pads with the GetVal command
and save the data back to the disk with the PutBB command.


There are three commands that control this memory.

	BuildScratch     Used to create the scratch pad in memory.

	                 The address of the scratch pad is returned
	                 and must be used on any future access to
                    this section of memory.


	ClearScratch     Used to blank the contents of the scratch
	                 pad. This DOES NOT free the memory. You MUST
	                 supply the address of the scratch pad you
	                 want to clear.


	KillScratch      Used to free the memory used by the scratch
	                 pad you allocated earlier. You MUST supply
	                 the address of the scratch pad to be killed.

                    The number of remaining open scratch pads is
                    returned. You can use this to tell if it is
                    safe to cause the GS CallerID to quit if you
                    want.
               
Examples:

	BuildScratch; MemAddr = Result

	ClearScratch MemAddr

	KillScratch MemAddr; ScratchCount = Result
@ENDNODE


@NODE REDISPLAY
@{U}Redisplay@{UU}    @{fg shine}@{U}ARexx Only Command@{UU}@{fg text}

	This command will cause the currently visible History or Black Book
	windows to be updated. This may be needed if you have a script that
	modifies data in the Black Book while one of the windows is open.
	
	If you call this and no window is open, the History window will
	quickly and that is all. No harm can come from this command.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Val
@{U}GetVal & PutVal@{UU}    @{fg shine}@{U}ARexx Only Command@{UU}@{fg text}


These two commands are used to get information from and give information
to GS CallerID. Everying on the list can be read, but only some things
can be written back to the program.

General Format:  GetVal <item> [scratch]
                 PutVal <item> [scratch] <NewValue>

@{fg fill}NOTE:@{fg text} Not all GetVal/PutVal items require the @{" scratch " link Scratch} pad memory.

@{U}ITEM@{UU}    @{U}DESCRIPTION / EXAMPLE                       @{UU}
  1     @{fg shine}Scratch pad count@{fg text}
        This is a good variable to check before you tell GS CallerID
        to Quit. If this is any value other than ZERO then there are
        open scratch pads in memory. This usualy means that some ARexx
        program is still running.

        @{B}GetVal 1; SPads = Result@{UB}



  2     @{fg shine}Black Book Records@{fg text}
        This is the number of records stored in the @{" Black Book " link BlackBook}.
        Required if you plan on accessing the @{" Black Book " link BlackBook} record by
        record. You don't want to go past the end of the file.

        @{B}GetVal 2; MaxBB = Result@{UB}



  3     @{fg shine}History Records@{fg text}
        This is the number of records stored in the History file.
        Required if you plan on accessing the History file record by
        record. You don't want to go past the end of the file.

        @{B}GetVal 3; MaxHist = Result@{UB}



  4    @{fg shine}Scratch Date@{fg text}
       This is a date from one of the scratch pads you have set up.

       A string with 2 forms of the date is returned. The first is
       unformatted and the second is formatted. '1103 11/03'

       No year is returned. You can figure that one out yourself.

       @{B}GetVal 4 MemAddr; Dates = Result@{UB}

       When you are filling this variable, you can only send 1 form
       of the date. It doesn't matter if it is formatted or not because
       only the numbers are stored.

       @{B}PutVal 4 MemAddr NewDate@{UB}



  5    @{fg shine}Scratch Time@{fg text}
       This is a time from one of the scratch pads you have set up.

       A string with 2 forms of the time is returned. The first is
       unformatted and the second is formatted. '831 8:31'

       The time is in 24 hour mode. You can calculate am/pm if you want.

       @{B}GetVal 5 MemAddr; Times = Result@{UB}

       When you are filling this variable, you can only send 1 form
       of the time. It doesn't matter if it is formatted or not because
       only the numbers are stored.

       @{B}PutVal 5 MemAddr NewTime@{UB}



  6    @{fg shine}Scratch DialMode@{fg text}
       This is the Dial Mode for the phone number.
       Acceptable values are the same as the @{" DefDial " link DefDial} values.

       @{B}GetVal 6 MemAddr; DialMode = Result@{UB}
       
       @{B}PutVal 6 MemAddr NewDialMode@{UB}



  7    @{fg shine}Scratch ModemMode@{fg text}
       This is the Modem Action mode this caler/entry.

            0 = Do Nothing
            1 = CLICK
            2 = BUZZ
            3 = Go to Shared mode, Do Action, Reset Modem
            4 = Close Port, Do Action, Reset Modem       

       @{B}GetVal 6 MemAddr; ModemMode = Result@{UB}
       
       @{B}PutVal 6 MemAddr NewModemMode@{UB}



  8    @{fg shine}Scratch Calls@{fg text}
       This is the number of times this caller/entry has called since
       the @{" Black Book " link BlackBook} was created.

       @{B}GetVal 8 MemAddr; Calls = Result@{UB}
       
       @{B}PutVal 8 MemAddr NewCalls@{UB}



  9    @{fg shine}Scratch Action@{fg text}
       The action to be preformed when this caller calls again.

       @{B}GetVal 9 MemAddr; Action = Result@{UB}
       
       @{B}PutVal 9 MemAddr NewAction@{UB}



 10    @{fg shine}Scratch Phone Number@{fg text}
       The phone number for this caller. No formatting is done. If
       you want the () and - you will need to put them in yourself.

       @{B}GetVal 10 MemAddr; Phone = Result@{UB}
       
       It doesn't matter if the new phone number is formatted or not.
       Only the digits are stored into memory.

       @{B}PutVal 10 MemAddr NewPhone@{UB}



 11    @{fg shine}Scratch Name@{fg text}
       The name of this caller. This is rather easy to understand.


       @{B}GetVal 11 MemAddr; Name = Result@{UB}
       
       @{B}PutVal 11 MemAddr NewName@{UB}



 12    @{fg shine}Scratch Address Line 1@{fg text}
       This is the first line of the caller's address.
       Usualy the building number and street.

       @{B}GetVal 12 MemAddr; Addr1 = Result@{UB}
       
       @{B}PutVal 12 MemAddr NewAddr1@{UB}



 13    @{fg shine}Scratch Address Line 2@{fg text}
       This is the second line of the caller's address.
       Usualy the City, State, and Zip

       @{B}GetVal 13 MemAddr; Addr2 = Result@{UB}
       
       @{B}PutVal 13 MemAddr NewAddr2@{UB}



 14    @{fg shine}Scratch Note@{fg text}
       This can be any comment. Actualy, any of the information
       other than the phone and action can be anything, but that
       would be silly. So I have placed this NOTE section in here
       specificlly for this purpos.

       @{B}GetVal 14 MemAddr; Note = Result@{UB}
       
       @{B}PutVal 14 MemAddr NewNote@{UB}
       
		 

 15    @{fg shine}New Calls@{fg text}
       This will return the number of NEW calls since the History
       window was last examined or when this field was last reset
       by an ARexx script. GetVal will return the number of new
       calls, and PutVal will set the number of new calls to zero.

       @{B}GetVal 15 ; NewCalls = Result@{UB}
       
       @{B}PutVal 15@{UB}



 16    @{fg shine}Ring Count@{fg text}
       If you need to know how many rings there has been, this
       is the variable you need. This is READ ONLY so there is no
       PutVal setting.

       @{B}GetVal 16 ; RingCount = Result@{UB}

@ENDNODE


@NODE GetHist
@{U}Get A History Record@{UU}    @{fg shine}@{U}ARexx Only Command@{UU}@{fg text}


This command will allow you to copy records from the History file into 
your scratch pad. You can then use this information any way you want.

One example would be the included @{" script " link Scripts} that prints the caller log. Or the
one that backsup the data in the history file to the @{" Black Book " link BlackBook} file.

You will need to supply the record number you want to read and the memory
address of your scratch pad.

Nothing is returned.


Example:
	GetHist Record MemAddr

@ENDNODE


@NODE GetBB
@{U}Get A Black Book Record@{UU}    @{fg shine}@{U}ARexx Only Command@{UU}@{fg text}


This command will allow you to copy records from the @{" Black Book " link BlackBook} file into 
your scratch pad. You can then use this information any way you want.

One example would be the included @{" script " link Scripts} that prints the contents of
the @{" Black Book " link BlackBook}.

You will need to supply the record number you want to read and the memory
address of your scratch pad.

Nothing is returned.


Example:
	GetBB Record MemAddr

@ENDNODE


@NODE PutBB
@{U}Put A Black Book Record@{UU}    @{fg shine}@{U}ARexx Only Command@{UU}@{fg text}


This command will allow you to write from your scratch pad back into
the @{" Black Book " link BlackBook} file. 

One example would be the included @{" script " link Scripts} that backsup the data in the 
history file to the @{" Black Book " link BlackBook} file.

You will need to supply the record number you want to read and the memory
address of your scratch pad.

Nothing is returned.


Example:
	PutBB Record MemAddr

@ENDNODE



@NODE OpenBB
@{U}Open the Black Book@{UU}

	This ARexx command opens the @{" Black Book " link BlackBook} window.	
	
	@{fg shine}@{U}ARexx Command@{UU}@{fg text}
	OPENBB       No paramiters
@ENDNODE

@NODE Contact
@{U}Contact Me!@{UU}

If you would like to get in contact with me for any reason, here is how...

	@{fg shine}InterNet:@{fg text} glenn@g-world.com
		
